{"title_page": "2008 Toronto Transit Commission strike", "text_new": "[[Image:LawrenceStationDamage.jpg|thumb|right|Damage caused during the labour disruption]]The '''2008 Toronto Transit Commission strike''' was a legal [[strike action]] by [[Toronto Transit Commission]] (TTC) unionized employees that began on April 26, 2008, at 12:01&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern time zone|EDT]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/torontonians-in-shock-after-transit-workers-strike-1.291607|title=Torontonians in shock after transit workers strike|date=2008-04-26|work=CTV News Toronto|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>[http://www.marketwire.com/mw/release.do?id=848785 TTC Settlement Rejected by Union]</ref> All bus, streetcar and subway service in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada, was suspended, leaving thousands of people stranded across the city.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/27/world/americas/27canada.html?ref=world|title=Toronto Transit Workers Strike Suddenly, Stranding Thousands|date=2008-04-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2008-04-26}}</ref> Although the strike action was legal, the [[Amalgamated Transit Union]] (ATU) Local 113 did not provide 48-hour notice of the service withdrawal as they had previously promised they would do. Instead, the ATU only provided 90 minutes' notice before the service withdrawal.<ref name=\"on strike\">{{cite news| title =  TTC workers on strike| publisher = [[The Toronto Star]]| url = https://www.thestar.com/News/GTA/article/418713 | date = 2008-04-26 | accessdate = 2008-04-26 | first1=Tess | last1=Kalinowski | first2=Noor | last2=Javed}}</ref> [[Bob Kinnear]], president of ATU Local 113, claimed that the lack of an advance notice was necessary to protect the TTC employees from \"angry and irrational members of the public\".<ref name=\"on strike\" />\n\n==General synopsis==\n{{Wikinews|Strike shuts down Toronto's transit system}}\nThe strike occurred when the two unions, ATU Local 113 and [[Canadian Union of Public Employees]] Local 2, voted 65% to reject the offer made on April 20, 2008.<ref name=\"on strike\" /> The result of the ratification vote was completed just after 10:00&nbsp;p.m. on April 25 and Torontonians and TTC employees were given approximately 90 minutes' notice before the job action began.\n\nThe rejected offer had offered TTC operators a 3% wage increase each year for three years. Some operators and maintenance staff were not pleased with the offer. There were also concerns over the injury compensation package and, according to some reports, [[outsourcing|contracting out]] work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transit.toronto.on.ca/archives/weblog/2008/04/25-ttc_worker.shtml|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503032846/http://transit.toronto.on.ca/archives/weblog/2008/04/25-ttc_worker.shtml|archivedate=2008-05-03|url-status=dead|accessdate=2008-04-26}}</ref> TTC employees voiced their concerns over the week prior to the strike.\n\n===Back-to-work legislation===\n{{Wikinews|Toronto transit workers ordered back to work}}\n[[Image:Dalton McGuinty 2007.JPG|thumb|left|[[Premier of Ontario|Ontario premier]] [[Dalton McGuinty]]]] At approximately 11:45&nbsp;p.m. on April 25, minutes before the strike began, [[Mayor of Toronto|Toronto mayor]] [[David Miller (Canadian politician)|David Miller]] held a news conference stating that the strike action was  \"unacceptable and irresponsible\" after the ATU failed to comply with the initial 48-hour strike notice and the subsequent rejection of the contract.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2008/04/26/ttc_strikes_as_deal_falls_apart.html|title=TTC strikes as deal falls apart|last=Kalinowski|first=Tess|date=2008-04-26|website=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> The mayor made a special request to [[Premier of Ontario|Ontario premier]] [[Dalton McGuinty]] asking him to seek back-to-work legislation, a special law that would block the TTC strike from continuing.<ref name=\":1\" /> By 12:30&nbsp;p.m. on April 26, the [[Government of Ontario|provincial government]] had signed an [[Order in Council]] allowing for a rare Sunday sitting of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario legislature]] to consider a bill (Bill 66) to order the union and its members back to work.<ref name=\"order\">{{cite news\n  | last = Benzie\n  | first = Robert\n  |author2= Curtis Rush\n  | title = Order in council signed\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | publisher = [[The Toronto Star]]\n  | date = 2008-04-26\n  | url = https://www.thestar.com/News/GTA/article/418772\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-26}}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2008, Bill 66 was unanimously passed by the Ontario Legislature, a process which only took 30 minutes. The law was quickly given [[Royal Assent|royal assent]] by [[David Onley]], the [[Lieutenant Governor of Ontario]], and it came into force at 2 p.m. The TTC was given a few hours to ensure the system was ready to operate and to build up service. Most transit service resumed by that evening.<ref>{{cite news\n  | title = TTC ordered back to work\n  | publisher = [[The Toronto Star]]\n  | date = 2008-04-27\n  | url = https://www.thestar.com/GTA/Transportation/article/418964\n  | accessdate = 2008-04-27\n| first1=Rob\n| last1=Ferguson\n| first2=Paola\n| last2=Loriggio\n| first3=Francine\n| last3=Kopun}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Offer==\n\n* Term: three years, expiring March 31, 2011\n* Wages: April 1, 2008 \u2013 3%; April 1, 2009 \u2013 3%; April 1, 2010 \u2013 3%\n* Vision Care: $300 every 2 years; plus $50 for exams\n* Dental Care: major restorative, including implants up to $2,500\n* Orthodontic: up to $4,000 (50% TTC coverage)\n* Physio & Chiro: $1,000 max ($35 per visit)\n* Long-term Disability: $2,550 max, per month\n\nSource: TTC<ref>{{cite news | url = http://torontoist.com/2008/04/ttc_agreement_d.php | title = TTC Strike 2008: Negotiated Settlement Details}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Organized labour|Ontario}}\n* [[2006 Toronto Transit Commission wildcat strike]]\n* [[Adam Giambrone]], city councillor and Chair of the TTC\n* [[Toronto Transit Commission personnel]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ttc.ca/ TTC website]\n* [http://ttcwatch.com TTC Watch]\n\n{{TTC}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2008 Toronto Transit Commission Strike}}\n[[Category:2008 labor disputes and strikes|Toronto Transit Commission Strike, 2008]]\n[[Category:Labour disputes in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Toronto Transit Commission]]\n[[Category:2008 in Canadian politics|Toronto Transit Commission Strike, 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:LawrenceStationDamage.jpg|thumb|right|Damage caused during the labour disruption]]The '''2008 Toronto Transit Commission strike''' was a legal [[strike action]] by [[Toronto Transit Commission]] (TTC) unionized employees that began on April 26, 2008, at 12:01&nbsp;a.m. [[Eastern time zone|EDT]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/torontonians-in-shock-after-transit-workers-strike-1.291607|title=Torontonians in shock after transit workers strike|date=2008-04-26|work=CTV News Toronto|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>[http://www.marketwire.com/mw/release.do?id=848785 TTC Settlement Rejected by Union]</ref> All bus, streetcar and subway service in [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada, was suspended, leaving thousands of people stranded across the city.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/27/world/americas/27canada.html?ref=world|title=Toronto Transit Workers Strike Suddenly, Stranding Thousands|date=2008-04-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2008-04-26}}</ref> Although the strike action was legal, the [[Amalgamated Transit Union]] (ATU) Local 113 did not provide 48-hour notice of the service withdrawal as they had previously promised they would do. Instead, the ATU only provided 90 minutes' notice before the service withdrawal.<